<br>
Allow me to give you a basic primer on how the world works in relation to your comment.<br>
<br>
They took an engine that was probably created up to 2 years before the initial launch of Everquest. They had no idea how popular everquest would be, and were designing around the current hardware of that time. Their beta's ended in 1999 I remember, so it is very possible that the design for this was first set out in 1997 or 1998.<br>
<br>
In case you did not know, it is very hard to completely replace a game engine without re-writing the entire game which is not something that is really possible in a popular online game. The work they did with Luclin while not to everyone's aesthetic tastes (i.e, some people did not like the look of the models) it can definitely be viewed as making lemonade out of lemons.<br>
<br>
I was a programmer for a number of years on PC and Playstation games for<br>
<br>
Electronic Arts (various sports titles)<br>
then<br>
Relic Entertainment (Homeworld)<br>
<br>
<br>
I have since tired of working 18 hour days and have moved into the business side of software development.<br>
